To verify that the union of set A and B is a superset of both set A and set B, we first need to find the union of set A and B.

The union of two sets is the set containing all the elements from both sets. So, the union of set A and B is:

A ∪ B = {2, 4, 6, 8}

Now, we need to check if A ∪ B is a superset of both set A and set B. A set is considered a superset of another set if it contains all the elements of the other set.

For set A:
A = {2, 4, 6}
A ∪ B = {2, 4, 6, 8}

A ∪ B contains all the elements of set A, so A ∪ B is a superset of set A.

For set B:
B = {4, 6, 8}
A ∪ B = {2, 4, 6, 8}

A ∪ B contains all the elements of set B, so A ∪ B is a superset of set B.

Since A ∪ B is a superset of both set A and set B, we have verified that the union of set A and B is a superset of both set A and set B.
